<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="84" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,684,1466]" pageId="1" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,312,684,710]" pageId="1" pageNumber="84">Description:—</emphasis>
Thallus corticolous, up to 
<quantity box="[615,672,684,711]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="84" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
in diam., loosely appressed to the substrate, sometimes flaking off, minutely felty, dull, pale mineral grey to olivaceous green; in section up to 100 µm thick, with abundant calcium oxalate crystals throughout the thallus. Hypothallus whitish, byssoid, composed of 1–2 µm wide hyphae. Prothallus up to 
<quantity box="[201,267,792,819]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="84" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
broad, byssoid, composed of interwoven and radiating hyphae, whitish. Pseudisidia numerous, irregular, globose, unbranched, byssoid, with abundantly projecting hyphae, mostly white but sometimes green in parts, up to 0.4 × 
<quantity box="[200,288,864,891]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="84" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
. Photobiont 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martius" authorityYear="1817" box="[428,570,864,890]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Trentepohliaceae" genus="Trentepohlia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Trentepohliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[428,570,864,890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="84">Trentepohlia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, single to aggregated, cells globose, 7–10 × 5–7 µm, yellowish green. Asci and pycnidia not seen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,684,1466]" pageId="1" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,523,936,962]" pageId="1" pageNumber="84">Chemistry and spot tests:—</emphasis>
Thallus and prothallus K+ yellow and then red, C–, P+ yellow, I–. TLC: norstictic acid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
